		<title type="html"><![CDATA[&quot;This ad will end in NaN&quot;]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=48697&#038;utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=this-ad-will-end-in-nan" />

		<id>https://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=48697</id>
		<updated>2020-10-08T10:55:53Z</updated>
		<published>2020-10-08T06:58:34Z</published>
		<category scheme="https://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll" term="Humor" />
		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[All too true. Seen on thehill.com: As Wikipedia explains, In computing, NaN, standing for Not a Number, is a member of a numeric data type that can be interpreted as a value that is undefined or unrepresentable, especially in floating-point arithmetic. Systematic use of NaNs was introduced by the IEEE 754 floating-point standard in 1985, [&#8230;]]]></summary>

					<content type="html" xml:base="https://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=48697&#038;utm_source=rss&#038;utm_medium=rss&#038;utm_campaign=this-ad-will-end-in-nan"><![CDATA[<p>All too true. Seen on thehill.com:<br />
<a href="http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/myl/AdEndsInNaN.png"><img title="Click to embiggen" src="http://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/myl/AdEndsInNaN.png" width="490" /></a><br />
<span id="more-48697"></span></p>
<p>As Wikipedia <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NaN" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">explains</a>,</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;"><span style="color: #000080;">In computing, <strong>NaN</strong>, standing for <strong>Not a Number</strong>, is a member of a numeric data type that can be interpreted as a value that is undefined or unrepresentable, especially in floating-point arithmetic. Systematic use of NaNs was introduced by the IEEE 754 floating-point standard in 1985, along with the representation of other non-finite quantities such as infinities.</span></p>
